<div id="review_77835130" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/77835130" />
    <a title="Geoff" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/126266-geoff"><img alt="Geoff" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1399505224p2/126266.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/77835130?book_show_action=true">Nov 15, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Geoff" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Geoff" href="/user/show/126266-geoff">Geoff</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143105145" href="/book/show/1576188.The_Street_of_Crocodiles_and_Other_Stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/126266-geoff?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer77835130" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer356477181154213076">Just intermittently rereading one of my absolute favorites... if you haven&apos;t read this collection (which includes Sanatorium Under the Sign of the Hourglass) do yourself a favor and read one of the great books. Schulz&apos;s sketches are equally great. Here is a lovely website dedicated to his art &amp; writing:<br/><br/><a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='http://www.brunoschulzart.org/'>http://www.brunoschulzart.org/</a><br/><br/>...and if you don&apos;t know Schulz&apos;s fate, read his wiki-biography or whatever, but be prepared for some genuine 20th century tragedy.<br/><br/>The first recorded Polish sentence </span>
  <span id="freeText356477181154213076" style="display:none">Just intermittently rereading one of my absolute favorites... if you haven't read this collection (which includes Sanatorium Under the Sign of the Hourglass) do yourself a favor and read one of the great books. Schulz's sketches are equally great. Here is a lovely website dedicated to his art &amp; writing:<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.brunoschulzart.org/">http://www.brunoschulzart.org/</a><br /><br />...and if you don't know Schulz's fate, read his wiki-biography or whatever, but be prepared for some genuine 20th century tragedy.<br /><br />The first recorded Polish sentence translates to something like "Let me grind, and you take a rest"... prophetic seeing the way the country was epically ground into the earth by the forces of history. But when you look at the astounding output of literature and art that survived and still today is finding a growing audience(Milosz, Gombrowicz, Wat, Herbert, Stanislaw Lem, Stanislaw Jerzy Lec, Szymborska, Jerzy Pilch, on &amp; on), it is just another affirmation of the true heroism of the artist, and the life-sustaining nature of creative works.</span>
  <a data-text-id="356477181154213076" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
